column1: How many seats will the United Russia party win in the 2021 Russian State Duma elections?
column5: ['Fewer than 226 seats', 'Between 226 seats and 299 seats', '300 seats or more', 'Russian State Duma elections will not be held before 20 September 2021']
column6: ['Elections and Referenda', 'Non-US Politics']

United Russia currently holds a super majority in parliament, winning 343 seats in 2016. However, election fraud has been a huge problem for Russian citizens. Leaders of the opposition party such as Alexey Navalny have been jailed or even exiled, and citizens who have supported opposition have been disenfranchised. Electronic voting and the severely limited ability to watch video streaming of polling stations by the CEC (Central Election Commission) have made it obvious that voting may be skewed. Most polls have reported United Russia to win around 300 seats, maintaining their majority. Despite this, the United Russia Party has seen its lowest popularity rating in 15 years - reported around and below 30% - suggesting the opposition will win seats in many of the single mandate districts where many United Russia candidates have done no campaigning at all. The amount of seats won by United Russia will likely depend on the severity of election fraud as well as voter turnout, which has also been low, reported at just around 31%.
Just a technicality at this point... I have no clue.

There is a solid lesson here for flailing democracies everywhere - a bad lesson - These elections are not about winning or even about preventing United Russia from taking 226 seats. They are about forcing the Kremlin to de-legitimize itself to the point where the system breaks down and it is forced to make concessions. The problem with this strategy is the Kremlin’s other option is to increase repression and smother protest, which has already happened.
The United Russia Party currently has the majority of 340+ seats and has since the 2016 Russian elections.
The United Russian Party already holds the majority. There is no evidence to suggest for the elections being postponed.

The United Russian Party currently has over 300 seats. There does not seem like there is enough opposition for them to lose lose a substantial number of seats. There is no evidence to suggest that the elections will not be held.

I chose the probabilities above because the past year has shown a much higher probability of Russia getting 300+ seats so I put most of the percentage in that catagory and some in the between 226 and 299 seats.

Putin seems to be changing things in his favour

Party of power is united, projects (paradoxically) both change (by admitting new and younger candidates through primaries) and continuity (with the same known people at the helm). They have many tools to keep the "constitutional" majority. Most probably, they get it with "one-mandate" seats.

1) Establishing base rate/trend: looking at all results since 2001, URP has gained over half of total seats each time, with an increasing trend (lots of variation and n=5) in the amount of seats in that the URP gets. 2) There is the question of whether the result is free or controlled. Freedom House speaks of 'controlled elections' but no full-blown dictatorship results (e.g. North Korea). Combined with 1), this means low chances of a result below 226. 3) In 2020 the results of the constitutional election showed significantly more support for the constitution than ex ante independent polling. This might be a sign that the polls underpredict results for the ruling party. 4) in a controlled setting, the risks of cancelling an election are low. The optics of cancelling elections are poor (costs are high) whereas you are not concerned about the result anyway (returns are low). 5) at the same time, polling shows Putin's popularity at an all-time low.

Based on historic trends alone, there's around 50% probability of more than 300 seats, but recent trends would suggest otherwise with support for United Russia significantly down since last election, when they won 339 seats. While the Kremlin did have good local elections in autumn, probably through heavy manipulation, given scale of social unrest in recent years, it might be too big a risk to rig the Duma elections too much this year, and so a simple majority in the 226-299 range is probably the most likely. That said, the creation of new systemic opposition parties enables United Russia party protect a large majority in the Duma without increasing its vote share, by splitting the opposition vote. This tactic could however be countered by the real opposition if they can promote 'smart voting' strategies to gather the opposition vote. Altogether, lean towards the simple majority option, therefore.
